│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash happens due to an assertion failure in    │
│ BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree for SplitVectorize nodes:                              │
│ OpTE1.isSame(ArrayRef(E->Scalars).take_front(OpTE1.getVectorFactor())). This  │
│ assertion expects that the first part of the scalars of the split node        │
│ matches the first combined subnode. The helper TreeEntry::isSame() is used to │
│ verify that relation. If isSame() returns false for valid configurations      │
│ (e.g., reordered entries or partial prefixes), vectorizeTree hits the         │
│ assertion and aborts.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows         │
│ extensive horizontal reduction vectorization and then a split alternate node. │
│ It also reports Combined entries being formed and reordering/extracts being   │
│ introduced. The failing assertion occurs specifically when validating the     │
│ first combined entry (front) against the prefix of E->Scalars. The log        │
│ indicates use of ReorderIndices and reuse masks and that the split combines   │
│ two entries (CombinedEntriesWithIndices.size()==2). The isSame()              │
│ implementation has a TODO comment saying it does not fully support matching   │
│ when nodes are just reordered and VL is not equal to the full Scalars size.   │
│ That aligns with our scenario where vectorizeTree compares a prefix           │
│ (take_front) of E->Scalars against OpTE1 with ReorderIndices.\n\n3. Root      │
│ Cause Analysis:\nTreeEntry::isSame(ArrayRef<Value *>) currently only supports │
│ two cases when ReorderIndices is non-empty:\n- VL.size() == Scalars.size():   │
│ it builds the inverse permutation Mask and compares using full mask.\n-       │
│ VL.size() == ReuseShuffleIndices.size(): it combines masks and compares.\nIf  │
│ VL is a strict subset (e.g., take_front of Scalars for a split prefix),       │
│ neither case matches, and isSame returns false even if the prefix aligns with │
│ the reordered Scalars. Consequently, the assertion in vectorizeTree fails.    │
│ The log and the code around isSame explicitly note a TODO about implementing  │
│ matching for reordering, which confirms the gap.\n\nTherefore, the first      │
│ transformation (vectorizeTree handling SplitVectorize) is relying on isSame   │
│ to verify correct composition, but isSame is too strict and doesn't handle    │
│ partial VLs with reordering.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should update  │
│ TreeEntry::isSame to properly handle partial VLs when ReorderIndices is       │
│ non-empty by constructing a sliced mask that corresponds to the VL            │
│ prefix/suffix sizes. The change is localized to the isSame function.\n\nEdit  │
│ (lines 3686-3713 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp):\n-      │
│ Enhance the ReorderIndices handling to:\n  - Build the inverse permutation    │
│ mask.\n  - If VL.size() == Scalars.size(), keep existing behavior.\n  - Else  │
│ if VL.size() < Scalars.size(), compare against the corresponding slice of the │
│ mask (e.g., take_front(VL.size())) to allow matching prefixes used by         │
│ SplitVectorize.\n  - Similarly, if ReuseShuffleIndices are used, combine      │
│ masks and then slice to VL.size() before comparison.\nThis preserves existing │
│ behavior while adding support for partial comparisons required by split       │
│ vectorization composition checks. The comparison logic continues to respect   │
│ PoisonMaskElem and Undef handling.\n\nNew pseudo-logic to insert:\n-          │
│ SmallVector<int> Mask; inversePermutation(ReorderIndices, Mask);\n- if        │
│ (VL.size() == Scalars.size()) return IsSame(Scalars, Mask);\n- if             │
│ (!ReuseShuffleIndices.empty()) { addMask(Mask, ReuseShuffleIndices); }\n- if  │
│ (VL.size() <= Mask.size()) return IsSame(Scalars,                             │
│ ArrayRef<int>(Mask).take_front(VL.size()));\n- return false;\n\nThis change   │
│ addresses the assertion's requirement by allowing isSame to return true when  │
│ comparing the first part of scalars under a reordering.\n\n5.                 │
│ Conclusion:\nThe failure is due to TreeEntry::isSame not supporting matching  │
│ of partial scalar lists when ReorderIndices is set, a known TODO. By          │
│ extending isSame to slice the mask to VL.size() and compare appropriately,    │
│ vectorizeTree's assertion will be satisfied for split nodes built from        │
│ reordered entries. This should fix the crash without altering the             │
│ vectorization semantics, enabling split vectorization to proceed              │
│ correctly."})                                                                 │
