│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash happens due to an assertion failure in BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree for   │
│ SplitVectorize nodes:                                                         │
│ OpTE1.isSame(ArrayRef(E->Scalars).take_front(OpTE1.getVectorFactor())). This  │
│ assertion expects that the first part of the scalars of the split node        │
│ matches the first combined subnode. The helper TreeEntry::isSame() is used to │
│ verify that relation. If isSame() returns false for valid configurations      │
│ (e.g., reordered entries or partial prefixes), vectorizeTree hits the         │
│ assertion and aborts.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows extensive horizontal reduction vectorization and then a   │
│ split alternate node. It also reports Combined entries being formed and       │
│ reordering/extracts being introduced. The failing assertion occurs            │
│ specifically when validating the first combined entry (front) against the     │
│ prefix of E->Scalars. The log indicates use of ReorderIndices and reuse masks │
│ and that the split combines two entries                                       │
│ (CombinedEntriesWithIndices.size()==2). The isSame() implementation has a     │
│ TODO comment saying it does not fully support matching when nodes are just    │
│ reordered and VL is not equal to the full Scalars size. That aligns with our  │
│ scenario where vectorizeTree compares a prefix (take_front) of E->Scalars     │
│ against OpTE1 with ReorderIndices.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ TreeEntry::isSame(ArrayRef<Value *>) currently only supports two cases when   │
│ ReorderIndices is non-empty:                                                  │
│ - VL.size() == Scalars.size(): it builds the inverse permutation Mask and     │
│ compares using full mask.                                                     │
│ - VL.size() == ReuseShuffleIndices.size(): it combines masks and compares.    │
│ If VL is a strict subset (e.g., take_front of Scalars for a split prefix),    │
│ neither case matches, and isSame returns false even if the prefix aligns with │
│ the reordered Scalars. Consequently, the assertion in vectorizeTree fails.    │
│ The log and the code around isSame explicitly note a TODO about implementing  │
│ matching for reordering, which confirms the gap.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the first transformation (vectorizeTree handling SplitVectorize)   │
│ is relying on isSame to verify correct composition, but isSame is too strict  │
│ and doesn't handle partial VLs with reordering.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ We should update TreeEntry::isSame to properly handle partial VLs when        │
│ ReorderIndices is non-empty by constructing a sliced mask that corresponds to │
│ the VL prefix/suffix sizes. The change is localized to the isSame function.   │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit (lines 3686-3713 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp):    │
│ - Enhance the ReorderIndices handling to:                                     │
│   - Build the inverse permutation mask.                                       │
│   - If VL.size() == Scalars.size(), keep existing behavior.                   │
│   - Else if VL.size() < Scalars.size(), compare against the corresponding     │
│ slice of the mask (e.g., take_front(VL.size())) to allow matching prefixes    │
│ used by SplitVectorize.                                                       │
│   - Similarly, if ReuseShuffleIndices are used, combine masks and then slice  │
│ to VL.size() before comparison.                                               │
│ This preserves existing behavior while adding support for partial comparisons │
│ required by split vectorization composition checks. The comparison logic      │
│ continues to respect PoisonMaskElem and Undef handling.                       │
│                                                                               │
│ New pseudo-logic to insert:                                                   │
│ - SmallVector<int> Mask; inversePermutation(ReorderIndices, Mask);            │
│ - if (VL.size() == Scalars.size()) return IsSame(Scalars, Mask);              │
│ - if (!ReuseShuffleIndices.empty()) { addMask(Mask, ReuseShuffleIndices); }   │
│ - if (VL.size() <= Mask.size()) return IsSame(Scalars,                        │
│ ArrayRef<int>(Mask).take_front(VL.size()));                                   │
│ - return false;                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ This change addresses the assertion's requirement by allowing isSame to       │
│ return true when comparing the first part of scalars under a reordering.      │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The failure is due to TreeEntry::isSame not supporting matching of partial    │
│ scalar lists when ReorderIndices is set, a known TODO. By extending isSame to │
│ slice the mask to VL.size() and compare appropriately, vectorizeTree's        │
│ assertion will be satisfied for split nodes built from reordered entries.     │
│ This should fix the crash without altering the vectorization semantics,       │
│ enabling split vectorization to proceed correctly.                            │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
